Assuming you are using Express, try this:

```
app.post(&#39;/webhook&#39;, line.middleware(config), (req, res) =&gt; {
  Promise
    .all(req.body.events.map(handleEvent))
    .then(result =&gt; res.status(200).json(result))
    .catch(err =&gt; res.status(500).end(&#39;Failed&#39;));
});
```

Alternatively, you could forward the error to the Express error handler using the `next` function:

```
app.post(&#39;/webhook&#39;, line.middleware(config), (req, res, next) =&gt; {
  Promise
    .all(req.body.events.map(handleEvent))
    .then(result =&gt; res.status(200).json(result))
    .catch(err =&gt; next(err));
});
```

If you don&#39;t necessarily need to use the assignment operator (i.e. if you consider the memcpy alternative viable) then you could write a non-operator assignment function instead:

    volatile foo&amp; volatile_assign(volatile foo&amp; f, const foo&amp; o) {
        if(&amp;f != &amp;o) {
            f.a = o.a;
            f.b = o.b;
        }
        return f;
    }

You can use a member function if you so prefer.

